category=Building an Application using Objects
description=<p>Commands and functions make up the fundamental parts of Revolution scripts.  This tutorial introduces you to using commands to do an action and using functions to look up or compute values.</p>
duration=4:38
filename=free_command_functions.avi
level=1
licensed=false
name=Commands and Functions
scripts=<p>Scripts Used in this Tutorial:</p>\n<p><font face="Courier New" size="12" color="#000000">on mouseUp</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier New" size="12" color="#000000">  answer error &#147;The world has stopped!&#148; titled &#147;Big Error!&#148;</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier New" size="12" color="#000000">end mouseUp</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier New" size="12" color="#000000">on mouseUp</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier New" size="12" color="#000000">  answer the time</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier New" size="12" color="#000000">end mouseUp</font></p>\n<p></p>\n<p><font face="Courier New" size="12" color="#000000">on mouseUp</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier New" size="12" color="#000000">  answer average(1,3,7)</font></p>\n<p><font face="Courier New" size="12" color="#000000">end mouseUp</font></p>\n<p></p>
title=Commands and Functions: The things an applcation can do
topics=<p>Key Topics Covered in this Tutorial:</p>\n<p>-&#9;When you want the computer to do something, you use a command</p>\n<p>-&#9;Commands are simple English-like words that get placed at the start of a line of script</p>\n<p>-&#9;Commands are colored blue in the Script Editor</p>\n<p>-&#9;Some common commands you may want to use include beep, answer, ask, print, put, save, cut, copy, paste and quit</p>\n<p>-&#9;How to view a list of commands using the Reference Documentation</p>\n<p>-&#9;When you want the computer to compute a value or return some information, you use a function</p>\n<p>-&#9;Functions are colored orange in the Script Editor</p>\n<p>-&#9;Functions appear after a command and can be written either with the word &#145;the&#146; or with brackets ()</p>\n<p>-&#9;Some common functions you may want to use include the time, the date, average() and round()</p>\n<p>-&#9;How to view a list of functions using the Reference Documentation </p>\n<p></p>